welcome to the seventh edition of the stanford seiu bargaining update in connection with stanford university's co page 1 issue 7 august 21 2009 from the stanford bargaining team welcome to the seventh edition of the stanford seiu bargaining update in connection with stanford university's contract negotiations with the service employees international union local 2007 seiu on july 7 2009 stanford and seiu began negotiations for a new collective bargaining agreement for approximately 1200 employees in schools and departments across the university including the slac national laboratory this weekly update which will be available during these negotiations will provide information about ideas and interests discussed options tentatively agreed to or other outcomes please disseminate the update as needed stanford and the seiu enter 8th week of bargaining stanford and seiu enter the 8th week of bargaining with the university and seiu bargaining teams focusing their efforts on resolving the remaining issues regarding the collective bargaining agreement which expires august 31 2009 the teams made significant headway during the past week at the main table and reached tentative agreements regarding the grievance process labor summit meetings and union member dues enrollment the grievance process was jointly revised to create a structure to improve grievance resolution early and at the department level while still maintaining third party resolution when needed the labor summit meeting process was jointly revised to provide ongoing communications and discussion regarding university finances health and safety issue resolution and joint training newly hired employees in the bargaining unit will now receive dues enrollment information at the time of hire randy livingston vice president for business affairs and chief financial officer met with representatives from the bargaining teams to provide additional information and answer questions regarding the university's financial challenges the negotiating teams continue to have meaningful discussion toward resolution regarding the most difficult issues dealing with grounds and the paint shop the union advanced supposals which may help address the budget deficit for land buildings and real estate and create a more competitive business model the parties continued the discussion regarding apprenticeship programs and expect to see further refinement of this supposal next week initial discussion occurred regarding the appropriate use of sick leave and the parties plan on continuing that discussion next week as well the teams will devote the entire next week to resolution of the outstanding issues including the economic package page 2 issue 7 august 21 2009 the parties resume negotiations on monday august 24 2009 the stanford bargaining team the stanford bargaining team includes david a jones director employee & management services human resources ann allison marsh senior manager employee & labor relations human resources cori bossenberry director of human resources school of medicine robert carpenter director of operations buildings and grounds maintenance land buildings and real estate megan davis associate vice president finance land buildings and real estate eric montell executive director stanford dining residential and dining enterprises and larry young director of human resources slac national laboratory
